<p><strong>Western Civilization: Jackson J. Spielvogel, 9th Edition</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question 1: What are the key characteristics of Western civilization?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> According to Spielvogel, Western civilization is characterized by its focus on reason, individualism, democracy, and science. It emerged from the classical traditions of Greece and Rome and has been shaped by Christianity, the Enlightenment, and the Industrial Revolution.</p>
<p><strong>Question 2: Describe the rise and fall of the Roman Empire.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The Roman Empire arose in the 8th century BCE and reached its peak in the 2nd century CE. It was a vast and prosperous empire, but its decline began in the 3rd century CE due to factors such as political instability, economic crisis, and invasions by Germanic tribes. The empire finally collapsed in the 5th century CE.</p>
<p><strong>Question 3: How did Christianity influence the development of Western civilization?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Christianity became the official religion of the Roman Empire in the 4th century CE and played a major role in shaping Western culture. It provided a moral framework, promoted literacy and education, and influenced art, architecture, and music. Christianity also influenced the development of political and social institutions, such as the concept of natural law.</p>
<p><strong>Question 4: What were the major events of the Enlightenment?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The Enlightenment was a philosophical movement that flourished in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries. It emphasized reason, science, and individual liberty. Major Enlightenment figures included Isaac Newton, Voltaire, and John Locke. The Enlightenment had a profound impact on Western society, leading to the American and French Revolutions and the rise of modern science.</p>
<p><strong>Question 5: How did the Industrial Revolution transform Western civilization?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The Industrial Revolution began in the 18th century and transformed Western economy and society. It led to the development of new technologies, the rise of factories, and an explosion in population. The Industrial Revolution also had social and cultural consequences, such as the emergence of the working class, the growth of cities, and the spread of new ideas through mass media.</p>